  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1445433417" />
    <a title="Kelly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2276205-kelly"><img alt="Kelly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1285872916p2/2276205.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1445433417?book_show_action=true">Nov 17, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kelly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kelly" href="/user/show/2276205-kelly">Kelly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780449235683" href="/book/show/1250999.On_the_Night_of_the_Seventh_Moon">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1445433417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6719115427342737681">I ended up liking this a surprising amount. Not even really as a romance--the hero is gone from it so long, and isn&apos;t all that vivid. More as a development of the heroine, who suffers a lot, insists on believing her truth, and finally ends up happy. And the setting is beautiful. It all felt way more meaty than <i>The Time of the Hunter&apos;s Moon</i>, which I read a few weeks ago, as if Holt had started phoning it in by the time she wrote the latter.</span>
  <span id="freeText6719115427342737681" style="display:none">I ended up liking this a surprising amount. Not even really as a romance--the hero is gone from it so long, and isn't all that vivid. More as a development of the heroine, who suffers a lot, insists on believing her truth, and finally ends up happy. And the setting is beautiful. It all felt way more meaty than <i>The Time of the Hunter's Moon</i>, which I read a few weeks ago, as if Holt had started phoning it in by the time she wrote the latter.</span>
